        keyVerse: { ref: 'Psalm 32:5', text: 'I acknowledged my sin to you, and I did not cover my iniquity; I said, "I will confess my transgressions to the LORD," and you forgave the iniquity of my sin.' },
        devotional: 'Psalm 32 and Psalm 51 are paired psalms of confession. Psalm 51 is David\'s prayer after Nathan confronted him about Bathsheba and Uriah — the most honest repentance prayer in the Bible. Psalm 32 is David\'s reflection on what it FEELS like to confess versus to conceal.\n\nNotice the contrast in Psalm 32. While David was silent — concealing his sin — his bones wasted away through his groaning all day long. His strength was dried up. The Lord\'s hand was heavy on him. THEN he confessed. And forgiveness was IMMEDIATE. The relief was complete.\n\nWhat needs CONFESSING today? Be specific. Most of us have something we have been managing quietly that needs to come into the light. The lie. The compromise. The bitter loop. The hidden pattern. Psalm 32 says concealment makes you sick. Confession opens the door. The God of David is the God who forgives the iniquity of your sin the moment you bring it.',
        prompt: 'Confession opens a door. What needs confessing?',
