        dayTitle: 'Day 4 · Sacred Lament',
        keyVerse: { ref: 'Psalm 42:11', text: 'Why are you cast down, O my soul, and why are you in turmoil within me? Hope in God; for I shall again praise him, my salvation and my God.' },
        devotional: 'The Bible contains MORE psalms of lament than psalms of praise. That should reshape how Christians pray. Psalm 42-43 (originally one psalm) is the famous "as the deer pants for streams" — a song of homesickness for God\'s presence. Psalm 88 is the bleakest psalm in the entire Psalter — it does not even end on a hopeful note. Just "darkness is my closest friend."\n\nGod gave us those psalms for a reason. Lament is SACRED. Some chapters of life require lament prayer, not bright-side prayer. The fact that Psalm 88 exists in canonized Scripture is permission to bring God your darkest content.\n\nWhat grief have you been carrying ALONE? Probably something. The loss. The dashed hope. The friend who never came back. The chapter you cannot get out of. Today, write your own lament — even just a few sentences. Take the lament tradition the psalmists modeled. God is not afraid of your darkness. He included Psalm 88 on purpose.',
        prompt: 'Lament is sacred. What grief have you been carrying alone?',
