        dayTitle: 'Day 10 · Song After Rescue',
        keyVerse: { ref: 'Psalm 18:2', text: 'The LORD is my rock and my fortress and my deliverer, my God, my rock, in whom I take refuge, my shield, and the horn of my salvation, my stronghold.' },
        devotional: 'Psalm 18 is David\'s LONG SONG after God rescued him from Saul and all his enemies. He stacks metaphors — rock, fortress, deliverer, refuge, shield, horn of salvation, stronghold. He cannot stop describing God. The psalm goes on for 50 verses. David was so overwhelmed by what God had done that he could not finish the song quickly.\n\nMost Christians do not write rescue songs. We notice the rescue and move on. The psalm is an invitation to STOP and RECORD what God has done. Write it down. Sing it. Tell it. Make it a marker so future you remembers when present you forgets.\n\nWhat RESCUE would you write a song about? Probably more than one. The rescue from a relationship that would have wrecked you. The rescue from a job that would have ruined you. The rescue from a substance, a doctrine, a path. The rescue from your own self-destruction at 19. Pick one today. Write a few sentences as YOUR psalm. Stack the metaphors. Let your gratitude be specific.',
