        day: 11, refs: ['Psalm 20', 'Psalm 21', 'Psalm 22'],
        dayTitle: 'Day 11 · The Cross-Prayer',
        keyVerse: { ref: 'Psalm 22:1', text: 'My God, my God, why have you forsaken me? Why are you so far from saving me, from the words of my groaning?' },
        devotional: 'Psalm 22 is the CROSS-PRAYER. Jesus quoted its opening verse from the cross — "My God, my God, why have You forsaken me?" Read the psalm slowly with that in mind. It is staggering how specifically the suffering is described, centuries before the cross.\n\nVerse 16: "they have pierced my hands and feet." Verse 18: "they divide my garments among them, and for my clothing they cast lots." Verse 7: "all who see me mock me." Verse 14: "I am poured out like water, and all my bones are out of joint." David wrote it about his own suffering, but the Holy Spirit was writing through him about Christ\'s.\n\nPay attention to v. 1 today. Jesus chose Psalm 22 to pray out loud from the cross. He was not just expressing forsakenness — He was pointing to a psalm that ends in triumph. By verse 22 the tone has shifted: "I will tell of your name to my brothers." Even in His worst moment, Jesus was preaching the gospel by where He started His prayer. The first verse names the agony. The last verses name the rescue. Both are true.',
